unsorted integer array nums. Return the smallest positive integer that is not present in nums.

You must implement an algorithm that runs in O(n) time and uses O(1) auxiliary space.

 Example 1:
Input: nums = [1,2,0]
Output: 3
Explanation: The numbers in the range [1,2] are all in the array.


class Solution {
public:
    int firstMissingPositive(vector<int>& nums) {

        int n = nums.size();

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){

            while(nums[i] >= 1 && nums[i] <= n && nums[i] != nums[nums[i]-1]){//tab tak karo jab tak correct placement na ho jaye isiliye while loop 
                swap(nums[i], nums[nums[i]-1]);  //swap(orignalindx,naya idx)
            }

        }

        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(nums[i] != i + 1)
                return i + 1;
        }

        return n + 1;
    }
};
intuition:CYCLIC SORT PATTERN:
For each index i:

If
nums[i] is between 1 and n
AND
nums[i] is not already in correct position
then swap it to its correct index.
Correct index formula:
correctIndex = nums[i] - 1

Why while loop (not if)?
Because after swapping, a new number arrives at index i.
Example earlier:
[3,4,-1,1]
After swap:
[-1,4,3,1]
Now another number might still need placement.
So we keep fixing until:
nums[i] is either
• out of range
• already correct
